ause they're too unknown. Too many uncertainties about safety and/or utility -as I said earlier, these are related, since deadweight determines utility, and is determined by the amount of extra mass devoted to safety.<br>
<br>
 Any links to or citations of NASA studies of atmospheric use of NTR for lower stages of launchers? Not upper stages or long-range nuclear powered bombers, but launchers.<br>
<br>
 I'm convinced about upper stages, even aside from this (quoted by Zaphod elsewhere)<br>
<br>
From the 1991 Mars Direct plan from NASA (Actually from Zubrin &amp; et-al from Martin Marietta before Lockheed bought it up)<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Use of a nuclear thermal rocket (NTR) third stage on the Ares would<br>
increase trans-Mars payload by 50%. The NTR stage would have a<br>
specific impulse of 900 s, a power of 900 MWth, and a thrust of<br>
45,000 lb.<br>
 Use of a NIMF (Nuclear rocket using Indigenous Martian Fuel) stage<br>
on the lander would provide the Habitation Module with the capability<br>
of leaping from one location on the Martian surface to another, using<br>
compressed Martian carbon dioxide from the atmosphere as propellant.<br>
This would allow 18 sites on the surface to be visited within the 550<br>
days of surface time, as opposed to just one for the baseline<br>
expedition.</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
 In light of the many &amp; varied sensible Shuttle proposals decided against in favor of the flying-cost-overrun camel we got, and things like the SSX and Sea Dragon for cargo and the HL-42 for people, I voted for chemicals.<br>
