Aha, finally we get to the heart of the matter. Who says nuclear engines have to run on Hydrogen. In the interests of safety we could just use a different form of reaction mass. Combustibility is not a prerequisite when the heat source for the propellant is not the propellant itself. Why not a completely harmless liquid that doesn't ignite at all? That would make nuclear rockets far safer than chemical ones in terms of likelihood of an explosion.<br>
