<br>
A failure of a conventional booster tends to result in the loss of the payload and the occasional dropping of some metal chunks where they don't belong.<br>
<br>
A failure of an exotic nuclear booster would result in an horrible radiological catastrophe.<br>
<br>
A one hundred percent failure rate of chemical boosters are less destructive then a single nuclear booster failure.<br>
<br>
You have made a serious mistake in confusing safety with reliability. You used the example of commercial Nuclear reactors. They are quite unreliable and equivalent performance in boosters would be disasterous.<br>
<br>
Power reactors use defense-in-depth to shield the public from the effects of the un-reliability. EBR-1 , Fermi-1, TMI-2, Chenobyl, etc wiped out their own cores. <br>
Also, massive destruction is rather common - look at the Brown's Ferry cable fire, or any number of tube failures in steam generators. <br>
Only the defense-in-depth of spray systems, containment vessels, backup cooling, etc provented (in most cases) the contamination of the environment. None, -NONE-, would be available in a nuclear launch booster. <br>
<br>
Furthermore, reactors respond to off-normal conditions by scramming, or tripping, or in plain language, TURNING OFF.<br>
These are common events.<br>
<br>
A nuclear booster, nearing orbit and having a common reactor trip (in order to avoid self-destruction), would be catastrophic.<br>
This is an image of MIR vaporizing as it reurns to Earth:<br>
<!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://images.spaceref.com/news/2001/03.23.01.startrek.iii.jpg"><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--><br>
Imagine this a reused nuclear booster with the power output equal to all the atomic reactors in France.<br>
<br>
----<br>
<br>
Conventional boosters are MUCH more reliable. Many launch families have 98-100% success (for example, the workhorse Atlas II was 100%). Even in the manned space boosters, only one failure has occured in the US launch series, since it began in 1961.<br>
